"Indeed, Captain. You should be en route by now, they were still in the mess hall picking up their rations." Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered by the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are being relocated to the forward operational base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a stronghold at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Depart for your squads and mount up."
The company dispersed into their respective squads, and the soldiers were assigned by the non-commissioned officers to the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days prior but knew little about them. He sat sideways, swinging his legs, while adjusting his backpack and the radio equipment connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" asked Nemic after they had settled in.
" Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal roam on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster, which was constantly turning its head to scan the surroundings.
" Yes, he's still with him," answered Cohren as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
"Every tank is moving out," spoke the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the convoy of tanks and Strykers roared to life as they set off. The Kronos tank, on which Cohren was riding, jolted as the brakes were released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Through the winter storms, the swamp areas had frozen and the forests were snow-covered, yet the mud was everywhere.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the beginning of the war?"
" Yes, Operation Firestorm," answered Cohren. "We thought the matter would be settled in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimated is a severe understatement," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We were not prepared for their arsenal and the number of soldiers they had. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly on the side of the Federation," said Orson defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"Say that now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you take cover the moment they hear a shot," explained Craith.
"Let's see about that," said Cohren laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are picking up heat signatures, approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his specialty glasses. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could see the signatures in the distance.
"yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his throat microphone.
"Squad, are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't make them out," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, fire only when under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they drew closer, one of them ran off hastily to retrieve something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were located. The figures lay down on the ground, taking up shooting positions.
"Shaw reported over the radio, 'We have enemy contact,' as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hill. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket streaked past and struck behind the formation, hitting the ground and scattering debris and rubble over one of the tanks. Another hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition exploded into the air."
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire," shouted the commander of the tank convoy over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew toward the hill and exploded, sending mud and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," Knoxx called out, observing the hill with a pair of binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they took off in a sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" asked Craith, while they watched.
"It looks like a capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentinels vanished into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hill, but quickly died down. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the safety of the convoy, they threw the figure onto the ground. She moaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure, who was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," answered the Sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
